<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Still with me?  Good.  Anyway...  I loved the movie, and I hated it.  The action scenes were IMO very well done.  Perhaps a bit over the top in the actual action though.  It got to be more funny than anything else after awhile.  But still visually very nice.  The underlying story was good.  A lot of references to religion or to literary works.  That helps the story because perhaps the story of religion is just a collective memory of a past matrix.  They also had some very nice foreshadowing..  Like Neo with the counsellor in the machine level.  They are so dependant on the machines.  They control the machines, they can shut them off..  But they would not be able to survive then.  Then later with Neo at the architect, he's faced with the same thing.  He can shut off the machines, or he can keep the people alive.  He chooses to shut off the machines, to end the power source.  We do not yet know the result of his choice though, as we have not seen the matrix since then, and we have not seen Zion since then.<br>
<br>
But the one thing that I missed, but the person I went with pointed out...  And the more I think about it the more it makes sense..  Is that..  We don't think they've ever left the matrix.  As you noticed Neo had power in the &quot;real world&quot; at the end of the movie.  Also, apparently (Again I missed this) when he is with the architect, and the scenes are flashing around behind him..  Some of the scenes are from the movie in the matrix..  Some are just generic footage.  However, some are also scenes from the &quot;Real world&quot;.  So, is the real world really real, or is it just the 7th version of the matrix?<br>
<br>
And this makes sense.  The flaw in the matrix is choice.  People choose not to believe the matrix.  However, what if the architect designed it so people would believe they already made the choice?  They could then keep the choice in check and keep the flaw from propogating, even if the old matrix is completely shutdown.  The new matrix then is just like the real world, creating the illusion that they have their freedom, when they are trapped.  It all fits so neatly with the story.<br>
<br>
As to 101..  In binary 101 would be 5.  This is the 6th matrix.  However computers often start counting from 0 not 1, so this is matrix 5 if you start with 0.  Don't know if thats what it really means but it could be. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tobrin>Tobrin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The Big Guy says I'm<br>
12 short of a Dozen! </span><br>  Posts: 54<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(5/20/03 11:43 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1566.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Merovingian</span><hr size=1> I absolutely loved the Matrix Reloaded; I thoroughly enjoyed watching it, but as I've thought back on the movie and pieced it all back together, I find I like it even more.<br>
<br>
And the killer thing is what a few have even mentioned already:  the &quot;real&quot; world is in actuality another matrix outside of the inner matrix (the city).<br>
<br>
There are several clues.  Agent Smith transferring into one of those guys in the &quot;real&quot; world, Neo retaining his powers in the &quot;real&quot; world... and most importantly, the spoon.<br>
<br>
What was the point of the child making sure that Neo got the spoon before he left to see the Oracle?<br>
<br>
Because there IS no spoon.  Just as the spoon in the matrix that he first saw wasn't real, so was the spoon delivered to him in Reloaded:  it is a message that Zion and the rest of the &quot;real&quot; world is actually another matrix.<br>
<br>
Which leaves us with a key question:  what is actually happening in the real world?  Is it run by machines as everyone believes?  Or is it possible that everything is a program being run by humans in the real world to develop AI?  Or something else?<br>
<br>
I can't wait until November.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
As for the style and visuals, I enjoyed that very much as well!  My friends all think they overdid the slow-mo and that the cgi was really poor.  I don't think so.  I agree that toward the end of the burly brawl, the cgi looked less convincing.  That's primarily because I am an animation geek and can pick up on a lot of it, but I have to say that despite the flaws, that sequence was one of the best cgi rendered sequences put to film yet!  (the Lord of the Rings is the only thing that truly comes close; Star Wars is too shiny/plastic/metallic to be as much of an achievement) <p>Tobrin &lt;Crusaders of Thunder&gt;<br>
